{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dill_ver02/data/sn91068695/00279559484/1949063001/0248.xml":{"full_text":"WHEN kidneys (unction badly and\nyou suffer a nagging backache,\nwith dizziness, burning, scanty or too\nfrequent urination ana getting up at\nnight; when you feel tired, nervous,\naft upset... use Doan's Pills.\nDoan's are especially for poorly\nworking kidneys. Millions of boxes\nm used every year. They are recom\nmended the country over. Ask your\nneighbor!\nDoans Pills\nNOTICE OF SALE OF LAND\nMORTH CAROLINA\nMcDowell county\nUnder and by virtue of an order\n\u00abf the Superior Court of McDowell\nCounty, North Carolina, made in\n\u2022ertafn special proceeding therein\nVending entitled: Viola Hunter Tay\nftir and husband, Albert J. Taylor;\nFlorence Hunter Ciaig and hus\n\u2022and, Charles R. Craig, Petitioners,\nvs. Katherine Hunter Brown, a wid\n\u00abw; John Harvey Hunter, Jr., and\nwife, Joy Hunter; Irene Hunter\nCreech and husband, Grover Creech,\nJr.; Charles T. Hunter and wife,\nWinifred Hunter; Katherine Hunt\ner Cooper and husband, Garnet\nCooper; Mildred Hunter Davis and\nlnsband, Earl F. Davis; William\nRobert Hunter and wife, Ida Garber\nHunter; Charlie Mae Gibson and\nlusband, William W. Gibson; Kath\nerine Norris and husband, Johnnie\nMorris, Jr.; Frances Conley, a single\nwoman; Nettie Powell Hunter, a\nwidow; and the Unknown and Un\nnamed Heirs at Law of Charles Jo\nseph Hunter, deceased, Defendants,\nthe undersigned Commissioner will\n\u2022n Saturday, July 9, 1949, at 12:00\n\u2022YJock, noon, at the Courthouse j\ndoor of McDowell County, North\nCarolina, offer for sale to the high\nest bidder for cash that certain\ntract of land lying and being in\nWebo Township, McDowell County,\nNorth Carolina, and more particu\nMrly described as follows:\nXKUlWlNliNU on a small black\nin W. C. Hobbs line and runs!\nKorth 134 poles to a large red oak;\nfhence North 82 deg. West 120\npoles to a stake in the Murphy line;\nAence South 134 poles to W. C.\nHobbs corner; thence South 82 deg.\nBast 120 poles to the beginning,\nand being the same tract of land\nas described and conveyed in that\n\u2022ertain deed dated January 11,\n1889, by James H. Atkins and wife,\nMary Atkins, to Charles J. Hunter,\nwhich deed is recorded in the Of-1\nfice of the Register of Deeds forj\nMcDowell County, North Carolina, j\n*v deed book 17 at page 141, to j\nwhich reference is made for fur\nft\u00abr desci'iption, said tract of land\nalso being known as the Charles Jo\nseph Hunter home place in Nebo i\nTownship, McDowell County, North\nCarolina. Excepting and reserving,\nSdwever, from the above described\nGrhct of land that certain six-acre\nfrict of land within the above de\nscribed boundary conveyed by,\nCharles J. Hunter and wife, to D. j\nS\u00bb. Hicks, by deed dated November!\n12, 1921, which deed is recorded in\nas id deed registry in deed book 60 j\nsit page 564, to which reference is\nalso made. j\nSaid sale will be made subject to i\nconfirmation by the Court, and a\nfen per cent deposit will be required\n\u2022n all bids received.\nThis 8th day of June, 1949.\nWILLIAM C. CHAMBERS,\nCbmmissioner.\nADMINISTRATRIX' NOTICE\nThe undersigned, having qualified;\nas admisitratrix of the state of Cate\nHemphill Greenlee, deceased late of j\nMcDowell County, North Carolina,\nthis is to notify all persons having',\nclaims against the estate of the said j\ndeceased to present them to the un- i\ndtersigned on or before the 24th day\nof June, 1950, or this notice will be\npleaded in bar of their recovery.\nAll persons indebted to said estate\nwDl please make immediate pay\nment to the undersigned.\nThis the 18th day of June, 1949.!\nMISS RUTH GREENLEE,\nAdministratrix of the\nEstate of Cate Hemphill Green- i\nlee, dec'd.\nADMINISTRATRIX NOTICE\nTO CREDITORS\nThe undersigned having qualified\nAdministratrix of the Estate of\nMrs. Minnie Neal Blanton, deceas-!\n\u00abd, late of McDowell County, North j\nCarolina, this is to notify all persons!\nlaving claims against the estate of j\n\u25a0aid decedent to exhibit the same i\nto iie undersigned at the Office of j\nProctor Dameron, Marion The-|\natre Building, Marion, North Caro-!\nUna, on or before June 17, 1950, or i\nthis notice will be pleaded in bar of\ntheir recovery. All persons indebted\nto said estate will please make im\nmediate payment;\nThis the 9th day of June, 1949.\nANNIE L. BLANTON,\nAdministratrix of\nMrs. Minnie Neal Blanton,\nDeceased.\nEXECUTRIX' NOTICE TO\nCREDITORS\nThe undersigned having qualified\nas executrix of the estate of Mrs.\nMaretta Walker Noblitt, deceased,\nthis is to notify all persons having\n\u2022laims against said estate to present\nthem to the undersigned at the of\nfices of Proctor Dameron, At\ntorneys, Marion Theatre Building,\nMarion, N. C., on or before May 27,\n1950, or this notice will be pleaded\nin bar of their recovery. All per\na\u00bbns indebted to said; estate will\nplease make immediate payment.\nThis 21st day of May, 1949.\nMts. Stella Walker King,\nExecutrix,-\nHealth and\nHe citify I\nDr. Sophia Bruntoi\nIf we truly love our follow men,\n,we will lose sight of ourselves in\ntrying to help others.\nDid you ever stop to think about\nthat good Samaritan? He might have\nsaid after he had rendered the suf\nferer first aid, \"Well, I've done all\nthat I can now. Somebody else will\nhave to see that he gets home. It's\ngetting late and my family will be\nuneasy about me. I can't lose any\nmore time with this man.\"\nBut he shouldered the responsi\nbility of taking care of the injured\nman. He took him to the inn, and\npaid to have him properly cared for\nuntil he was able to continue on his\njourney.\nThe Samaritan had his own pro\ngram seriously upset. It cost him\ntime, money and inconvenience. He\nmade sacrifices to help another in\ndistress. Here was personal minis\ntry that involved self-abnegation,\nbut it brought real happiness in the\nway that Jesus sought.\nAs we endeavor to lead others out\nof discouragement and loneliness,\nhappiness comes to us as the result.\nLet us not go out seeking happi\nness for ourselves; for if we do, it\nwill elude us. Let us not ponder on\nwhat we are going to get out of life,\nbut what we are going to put into\nit for our fellow men.\nLet us stop complaining and per\nmit our minds to dwell on God's\ngoodness to us. Let us give thanks\nfor all the mercies that crown our\nlives and bring to us a realization of\nour heavenly Father's protecting\ncare over us.\nOne reason why there are so\nmany sick people in the world to\nday is because they are miserable\nand fearful and thereby ruin their\nnerves and destroy health.\nHappiness comes from within but\nwe must invite it by preparing well.\nMOTOR VEHICLES\nAutomobile production so far in\n1949 has exceeded 3,000,000 cars\nand trucks. Annual output at this\nrate would hit an all-time high\nmark of 6,000,000.\nNOTICE OF SALE OF LAND\nUNDER DEED OF TRUST\nTake notice, that whereas, Sam\nuel Avery and wife, Alma Avery,\non the 16t.h day of August, 1948, j\ndid execute and deliver to J. N. Mor\nris, Trustee, a deed of trust which\nis recorded in the office of the Reg\nister of Deeds for McDowell, North\nCarolina, in Deed of Trust Book 65,\nat page 81, conveying the lands\nhereinafter described to secure an:\nindebtedness therein described, and\nin said deed of trust power of sale I\nwas given in default of payment of1\nthe indebtedness thereby secured.!\nAnd whereas, the holder of the j\nindebtedness as secured by the!\naforementioned deed of trust has\ndemanded that the undersigned\nforeclose and sell the land as de-!\nscribed in said deed of trust, and as'\nhereinafter described, for the pur-'\n[>ose of satisfying the indebtedness\nsecured by said deed of trust.\nNow, therefore, the undersigned\nwill, on Monday, the 25th day ofi\nJuly, 1949, at 12 o'clock noon, at\nthe Courthouse door, at Marion,\nMcDowell County, North Carolina,\nfor the purpose of satisfying the in\ndebtedness as secured by said deed\nof trust, offer for sale to the high\nest bidder, for cash, the following\ntracts of land, lying and being in\nMarion Township, McDowell Coun\nty, North Carolina, to-wit:\nBeing ten (10) lots, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5,\n6, 7, 8, 9 and 10, in Block No. 9,\nof the Subdivision known as Mt.\nIda Park Addition to the Town of\nMarion, said lots having a front\nage of 250 feet on Ridley Street,\ndescribed and contained in a certain\nmap made by T. D. Harris, C. E.,\nwhich Map is recorded in the office\nof the Register of Deeds for Mc\nDowell County, North Carolina, in\nMap Book 1, at page 148, to which\nreference is heveby made.\nThe perpetual right and ease\nment of egress, ingress, and regress\nover and upon the following strip\nof land: BEGINNING at an iron\npin at the Southeast corner of Lot\nNo. 31, in Block No. 8 of said Mt.\nIda Park Addition, and runs North\n(var. 4 deg. 30 min.) 150 feet to\nan iron pin in the margin of the\nMarion-Sugar Hill road; thence\nwith the Southern margin of the\nMarion-Sugar Hill road South 69\nWest 10 feet to an iron pin in said\nmargin of Marion-Sugar Hill road;\nthence South (var. 4 deg. 30 min.)\n146 feet to Ridley Street; thence\nEast (4 deg. 30 min. var.) along\nthe North Margin of Ridley Street\n10 feet to the beginning. Said strip\nof land to be kept open and unob\nstructed at all times and said right\nand easement appurtenant to and\nruns with the aforementioned lot of\nland.\nAnd being the same lands as de\nscribed in that certain deed dated\nthe 2nd day of August, 1948, by T.\nR. Morris and wife, Lenore E. Mor\nris, to Samuel Avery and wife, An\nna M. Avery, recorded in the office\nof the Register of Deeds for Mc\nDowell County, N. C., in Deed Book\n102, at page 501, to which refer\nence is hereby made for further de\nscription.\nSaid sale will be subject to con\nfirmation as provided by law.\nThis 21st day of June, 1949.\nJ. N. MORRIS, Trustee.\nDeai' Louisa\nI am very much in love with a\nfellow that I alh, afraid I cannot\ncatch. Whenever I pass this fellow\non the road he never stops to speak\nwhen I would like for him to.\nI have talked to other fellows\ntrying to find just where I stand\nand I have never received a very\nsatisfactory answer. I have known\nhim for a year and have only had\nabout a dozen dates with him.\nHe is very magnetic and I lay\nawake at night thinking about him\nand at work I keep thinking about\nhim.\nPlease help me, I am desperate!\nSorrowful\u2014Joyce.\nAnswer:\nI am afraid you will have to help\nyourself, Joyce. You are evidently\nfascinated by a boy who doesn't\ncare anything about you. The mere\nfact that he doesn't noti\" 3 you out\nin public is certainly, evidence en\nough that he doesn't care anything\nabout you and he must give othef\npeople the same impression as none\nof them seem to encourage you a\nbout his feelings for you.\nThe best thing you can do is to\nsnap out of it and try to get your\nmind off him. Personally, I would\nhave too much pride to date a fel\nlow who did not notice me in pub\nlic.\nLOUISA.\nDear Louisa\nI have three small children and I\nenjoy them very much. One of my\n1 friends thinks that I am making a\nmistake staying with them so much\ninstead of helping with civic work.\nMy husband enjoys being with the\nchildren too and we have good tim\nes together on picnics and other\noutings. Do you think we are selfish\nor liable to get in a rut?\nYoung Mother\u2014Iowa.\n\n\nAnswer:\nI can't think of any better work\na young mother can do than to take\ncare of three small children, teach\ning them to become good citizens\nand giving them priceless memories\nof a happy childhood. You and your\nhusband will no doubt enjoy the\nrewards of your labor many times\nover 1n the years to come.\nCivic work Ms fine, but let those\nwomen do it who can without ne\nglecting their children. It is nice to\nhave some outside interests, but as\nlong as you and your husband are\nsatisfied and the children are hap\npy, pay no attention to what your\nfriends have to say.\nLOUISA.\nAddress your letters to:\n\"Louisa, P. O. Box 532\nOrangeburg, S. C.\nThe American Bible Society dis\ntributed 9,716,251 copies of the\nScriptures in 151 languages in 1948.\nDistribution in 40 foreign countries\ntotalled 5,668,336, and in the Unit\ned States 4,047,915.\nExtension Service\nAnnounces Release\nOf Annual Report\nDirector I. 0. Schaub announced\nthis week that the 1948 annual re\nport of the State College Extension\nService has been released and is\nnow available for distribution.\nEntitled \"Better Rural Living\"\nthe 36-page report presents the\nprogress Extension workers have\nmade in carrying their program to\nthe farm families and portrays how\nthe rural people have improved\ntheir living conditions through bet\nter farming and homemaking prac\ntices.\nAn introductory statement of the\nreport points out that \"things are\ndifferent on the farm today as com\npared to yesteryear. The farmer is\nno longer indentified as a man clad\nin blue denim overalls with his\narms sturdily set to guide the plow, j\nInstead, he is looked upon as a j\nbusinessman, wearing a business-,\nnan's clothes, driving a business\nman's car, living in a comfortable j\niome, and occupying an important j\nalace in the governing bodies of\u00ab\nlis community, county, state and\nlation.\"\nFacts presented in the report\n=how that 233,157 farms showed\nlefinite changes in practice during\n1948 as a result of the Extension\nprogram; a total of -296,434 farm\n>r home visits were made during\nDhe year by Extension workers;\nmore than 648,000 telephone in\nquiries were answered; 1,089^474\nlelpful publications on farming and\nlomemaking were printed and dis\ntributed; and more than 274,000\nfarm families were informed by\nsome phase of Extension.\nThe Extension Service now has\nmore than 600 workers located at\nState College and in each of the\n100 counties of the state. Their\nwork is aimed at helping the rural\npeople. Some of the results of their\nwork during 1948 is presented in\nthe report. Anyone desiring a copy\nof the report should write to the\nAgricultural Editor at State Col\nlege.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nPointing out that there has been\na relaxation of inflationary pres\nsures, evident in late 1948. Secre\ntary of Commerce Charles Sawyer\ndeclared that \"by any normal stand\nard of historic comparison, our\n\"business situation is good.\" Wheth\ner this situation would coi.tinue, he\nsaid, \"will depend entirely as much\nupon psychological factors as upon\nmaterial factors.\"\nSHE RECOVERS QUICK\nA woman lay very ill. Having\nbrought up a clever orphan girl, the\nsick woman called the orphan to her\nand said: \"I shall soon leave my lit\ntle children motherless. They know\nyou and love you, and after I am\ngone I want you and my husband to\nmarry.\"\nThe young woman, bursting into\ntears, said, \"We were just talking\nabout that.\"\nThe wife recovered.\nRead The Progress for local and\ncurrent events.\nWHO KNOWS?\n1. How many war veterans and\nsurvivors get U. S. pensions?\n2. How much has the U. S. paid\nout in pensions since 1776?\n3. What ex-President served in\nCongress?\n4. How many countries are mem\nbers of the North Atlantic Pact?\n5. Who leads the commander-in\nchief of the Western European Un\nion?\n6. How many completely \"dry\"\nStates are there in the U. S.?\n7. How many soft-coai miners are\nmembers of the U. M. W.?\n8. Who is our Ambassador to\nFrance?\n9. How long did the Spanish Civil\nWar last?\n10. Who is the newly-appointed\ntreasurer of the U. S.?\n(See answers on page 7)\nBENEFIT BY THIS\nGOOD NEWS\nCOMBINATION\nYOUR HOME TOWN PAPER\nfive* you eempliti, dependable\nlocal newt. You aeed to know all\nthat it going on when you live.\nBut you live alto in a\nWORLD where big eventt are in\nthe making eventt which can\n\u25a0\u2022eon to much to you, to your\njob, your home, your future. For\nconitructive report! and interpre\ntation! of national and interna\ntional newt, there it no tubttitute\nfor THE CHRISTIAN SCIENCE\nMONITOR.\nEnjoy the benefitt of being\nbett informed\u2014locally, nationally,\ninternationally with your local\npaper and The Chrittian Science\nMonitor.\nLISTEN Tuetday night* over\nABC ttationt to \"The Chrittian\nScience Monitor Yiewt the Newt.\"\nAnd ute thit coupon\ntoday for a tpecial in- 0, 8\ntroductory tubtcription. j) J Fundi\nThe Christian Science Monitor\nOne, Norway St., Boston 15, Mast., U.S.A.\nPlease send me en Introductory\nsubscription to The Christian Science\nMonitor 26 Issues. I enclose $1.\n\n(name)\n(address)\n(city) (tone) (state)\nPB7\nWomen now find 2-way\nhelp for old problem\nWhat to do for woman's oldest\nproblem, functional monthly pain?\nMany a girl and woman has found\nthe answer in Cardui's 2-way help.\nYou Bee, CA:o)in; may make things\nlots easier for you in either of two\nways: (1) started 3 days before\n\"your time\" and taken as directed\nbn the label, It should help relieve\nfunctional periodic pain; (2) taken\nthroughout the month likes a tonic,\ntt should improve your appe tite, aid\ndigestion, and thus help build up\nresistance for the trying days to\ncome. Cakdtji la scientifically pre\npared and scientifically tested. If\nyou suffer -at thoeq SKfelU ttow\",\nget Cambvx today*\nWestmoreland- Hat&Kjns\nFuneral Service\nImbulance\n\"Phone 4-76\n\"Phone 276 220 S. Main St.\nMODERN FOOD PRESERVATION\nINCLUDES HOME FREEZING\nFreezing more Jhon arty other method of\nfood preservation retains original color,\ntexture, flavor, and nutritional content and\nrequires only a minimum of time\nWhat varieties of fruits and vegetables are best\nsuited to freezing? How best to process foods\nfor freezing? Hew to cook frozen foods? These\nare questions Duke Power Company Home\nService Specialists are studying in order to be\nqualified to help you with your home freezing\nproblems\nDURE POWER COMPANY\n~tfut j^cdnumtj (JiudltuM\nrruw w Amitfwujtcit\nEVERYONE TALKS\nABOUT THE\nAll over America, on big farms and little farms, it's proving\nitself \"The Year 'Round Tractor\".. whining fame- for all\n'round performance, all 'round the farm, all year 'found.\nYoull respect the Ford Tractor for the way it buckles down\nto heavy Jobs of plowing or discing. You'll like it, and Dearborn\nEquipment, too, for the way you can do such jftbs as scraping,\nleveling, loading, ditching, terracing, excavat\ning, digging post holes or sawing wood. Most\nDearborn implements lift or lower at a touch\non the Ford Hydraulic Touch Control. Ask\nfor a demonstration.\nSain Tractor Implement Co\n117 East Court St. Marion, N. C.\nLand Deeds, Mortgage Deeds, Chattel Mortga\nges, State Warrants, Trespass Notices, Etc., foe\nsale at THE MARION PROGRESS office. j","height":"31324","width":"21356"}}
